SIMPLE: sensible
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Sensible
<hw>Sen"si*ble</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[F., fr. L.
<ets>sensibilis</ets>, fr. <ets>sensus</ets> sense.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Capable of being perceived by the senses; apprehensible through the
bodily organs; hence, also, perceptible to the mind; making an
impression upon the sense, reason, or understanding; <as>as,
<xex>sensible</xex> heat; <xex>sensible</xex> resistance</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Air is <qex>sensible</qex> to the touch by its motion.</q>
<rj><qau>Arbuthnot.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The disgrace was more <qex>sensible</qex> than the pain.</q>
<rj><qau>Sir W. Temple.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Any very <qex>sensible</qex> effect upon the prices of things.</q>
<rj><qau>A. Smith.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Having the capacity of receiving impressions from
external objects; capable of perceiving by the instrumentality of the
proper organs; liable to be affected physically or mentally;
impressible.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Would your cambric were <qex>sensible</qex> as your finger.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Hence: Liable to impression from without; easily
affected; having nice perception or acute feeling; sensitive; also,
readily moved or affected by natural agents; delicate; <as>as, a
<ex>sensible</ex> thermometer</as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧With affection wondrous
<xex>sensible</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Perceiving or having perception, either by the
senses or the mind; cognizant; perceiving so clearly as to be convinced;
satisfied; persuaded.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He [man] can not think at any time, waking or sleeping, without
being <qex>sensible</qex> of it.</q> <rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They are now <qex>sensible</qex> it would have been better to
comply than to refuse.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Having moral perception; capable of being affected
by moral good or evil.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>Possessing or containing sense or reason; gifted
with, or characterized by, good or common sense; intelligent;
wise.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Now a <qex>sensible</qex> man, by and by a fool.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Sensible note</b></col> <it>or</it>
<col><b>Sensible tone</b></col></mcol> <fld>(Mus.)</fld>, <cd>the major
seventh note of any scale; -- so called because, being but a half step
below the octave, or key tone, and naturally leading up to that, it
makes the ear <xex>sensible</xex> of its approaching sound. Called also
the <altname>leading tone</altname>.</cd> -- <col><b>Sensible
horizon</b></col>. <cd>See <er>Horizon</er>, <pos>n.</pos>, 2.
<sd>(a)</sd>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Intelligent; wise.</syn> --
<usage><er>Sensible</er>, <er>Intelligent</er>. We call a man
<xex>sensible</xex> whose judgments and conduct are marked and governed
by sound judgment or good common sense. We call one
<xex>intelligent</xex> who is quick and clear in his understanding,
<it>i. e.</it>, who discriminates readily and nicely in respect to
difficult and important distinctions. The sphere of the
<xex>sensible</xex> man lies in matters of practical concern; of the
<xex>intelligent</xex> man, in subjects of intellectual interest.
⟦ldquo⟧I have been tired with accounts from <xex>sensible</xex> men,
furnished with matters of fact which have happened within their own
knowledge.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Addison.</au> ⟦ldquo⟧Trace out the numerous
footsteps . . . of a most wise and <xex>intelligent</xex> architect
throughout all this stupendous fabric.⟦rdquo⟧
<au>Woodward.</au></usage>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sensible</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Sensible
<hw>Sen"si*ble</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Sensation; sensibility.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧Our temper
changed . . . which must needs remove the <xex>sensible</xex> of
pain.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That which impresses itself on the sense; anything
perceptible.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Aristotle distinguished <qex>sensibles</qex> into common and
proper.</q> <rj><qau>Krauth-Fleming.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>That which has sensibility; a sensitive being.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This melancholy extends itself not to men only, but even to
vegetals and <qex>sensibles</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Burton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sensibleness</ent>⟦br⟧
